    Block {
      BlockType		      SubSystem
      Name		      "More Info1"
      Ports		      []
      Position		      [890, 645, 917, 670]
      DropShadow	      on
      ShowName		      off
      TreatAsAtomicUnit	      off
      MaskDisplay	      "disp('?')"
      MaskIconFrame	      on
      MaskIconOpaque	      on
      MaskIconRotate	      "none"
      MaskIconUnits	      "autoscale"
      System {
	Name			"More Info1"
	Location		[66, 149, 908, 761]
	Open			off
	ModelBrowserVisibility	off
	ModelBrowserWidth	200
	ScreenColor		"white"
	PaperOrientation	"landscape"
	PaperPositionMode	"auto"
	PaperType		"usletter"
	PaperUnits		"inches"
	ZoomFactor		"100"
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "Notice the 120 Hz oscillations in the DC vo"
"ltage and currents during the fault. When the fault is cleared at t=0.7 s,\nt"
"he VDCOL operates and reduces the reference current to 0.3 pu. The system rec"
"overs in approximately 0.4 s after fault clearing."
	  Position		  [329, 837]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "In the DC Fault Timer and Forced Delay Time"
"r blocks, change the multiplication factor of 1 in the Transition Times to 10"
"0,\nso that the DC fault is now eliminated.  In the AC Fault timer, change th"
"e multiplication factor in the Transition Times to 1,\nso that a 6 cycles lin"
"e-to-ground fault is now applied at the rectifier. Restart the simulation. "
	  Position		  [344, 787]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "AC line-to-ground fault"
	  Position		  [104, 752]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "Disconnect the Step Up & Down block in orde"
"r to eliminate the step disturbance applied on the reference current.\nIn the"
" DC Fault Timer and Forced Delay Timer blocks, change the multiplication fact"
"or of 100 in the Transition Times to 1,\nso that a fault is now applied at t="
"0.6s. Open the I_DCfault scope to observe the fault current. Restart the simu"
"lation.  "
	  Position		  [319, 622]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "At fault application the DC current quickly"
" increases to 2.3 pu and the DC voltage falls to zero at the rectifier. \nThi"
"s DC voltages drop is seen by the Voltage Dependant Currrent Order Limiter (V"
"DCOL) which reduces the reference current to 0.3 pu at the rectifier.\nA DC c"
"urrent still continues to circulate in the fault. Then, a t=0.65 s, the recti"
"fier alpha firing angle is forced to 165 degrees by the protection systems (n"
"ot simulated).\nThe rectifier now operates in inverter mode. The DC line volt"
"age becomes negative and the energy stored in the line is returned to the AC "
"network, \ncausing rapid extinction of the fault current at its next zero-cro"
"ssing. Then, alpha is released at t=0.7 s and the normal DC voltage and curre"
"nt\n recover in approcxximately 0.3 s. \n "
	  Position		  [419, 697]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "DC line fault"
	  Position		  [74, 587]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "Start-up"
	  Position		  [44, 407]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "DEMONSTRATION"
	  Position		  [74, 307]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "A 1000 MW (500 kV, 2kA) DC linterconnexion "
"is used to transmit power from a 500 kV, 5000 MVA,60Hz network. \nto a  345 k"
"V, 10 000MVA, 50Hz network.\n\nThe rectifier and the inverter  are 12-pulse c"
"onverters using  two 6-pulse Universal briges connected in series. \nOpen the"
" two converter subsystems to see how they are built. The converters are inter"
"connected through a 300 km distributed parameter \nline through and 0.5 H smo"
"othing reactors. The converter transformers are modelled with Universal Trans"
"former blocks. \nThe transformer tap changers are kept at a fixed tap. Open t"
"he two transformer blocks to see the factors applied \non the primary voltage"
" (0.90 on rectifier side; 0.96 on inverter side). The reactive power required"
" by the converters is provided \nby a set of filters (C bank plus 11th, 13th "
"and  high pass filters; total 600 Mvar on each side).\nOpen the AC filter sub"
"systems to see the filter toplogy.  Two circuit breakers are used to apply fa"
"ults on the rectifier AC and DC sides.\n\nThe rectifier and inverter control "
"systems use the  Discrete 12-pulse HVDC Control block of the Extras/Control l"
"ibrary.\n The power system and the control system are both  discretized (Samp"
"le time= Ts).\nA description of the control systems is provided in the HVDC T"
"ransmission System Case Study of the User's Manual."
	  Position		  [339, 197]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "This demonstration  illustrates steady-stat"
"e and transient performance\nof a 12-pulse,  1000 MW (500 kV-2kA) 50/60 Hz HV"
"DC transmission system"
	  Position		  [379, 27]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "CIRCUIT  DESCRIPTION"
	  Position		  [89, 87]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "Notice that the system is discretized, usin"
"g sample time Ts; Specify Ts=50e-6 in your Matlab window.\nThe system is prog"
"rammed to start and  reach a steady state. \nThen, a step is applied on the r"
"eference current to observe the dynamic response of the regulators.\nStart th"
"e simulation and observe the following events on the RECTIFIER and  INVERTER "
"scopes"
	  Position		  [259, 352]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "The reference current is ramped from zero t"
"o 1 pu (2kA) in 0.4 s. The DC current and voltages start from zero and reach "
"steady-state\n in approximately 0.5 s.The rectifier controls the current and "
"the inverter controls the voltage.Trace 1 of both RECTIFIER and INVERTER scop"
"es\n shows the DC line voltage (1pu=500 kV). Trace 2 shows the the reference "
"current and the measured Id current (1pu=2kA).\nIn steady-state, the alpha fi"
"ring angles (trace 3) are 18 degres and 142 degrees respectively on the recti"
"fier and inverter side.  "
	  Position		  [364, 452]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "At t=0.6 s, a 0.2 pu step is applied on the"
" reference current (decrease from 1 pu  to 0.8 pu ).\nAt t=0.75s,another step"
" is applied to set the reference back to 1 pu. \nObserve the response of the "
"current regulator . It stabilizes in  approximately 0.05 s "
	  Position		  [254, 542]
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  "Step reponse of regulators"
	  Position		  [114, 502]
	  FontSize		  14
	  FontWeight		  "bold"
	}
	Annotation {
	  Name			  " S. Casoria ; Hydro-Quebec (IREQ)"
	  Position		  [370, 54]
	}
      }
    }
